Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` for the hardware/software back button, and use `Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior` for the Shell nav bar:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            ConfirmDiscard();
            return true; // cancel navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async void ConfirmDiscard()
    {
        bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (discard)
        {
            _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button in XAML:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:toolkit="...">
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand BackCommand => new Command(() =>
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        ConfirmDiscard();
    else
        Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
});
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles Android hardware/gesture back. Return `true` to cancel.
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the Shell toolbar back button — it **won't** auto-navigate, so you must call `GoToAsync("..")` yourself.
- `TextOverride` replaces the arrow with your "Cancel" text.
